6","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"The volume of a spherical bubble increases at a constant rate of 5 cm3s-1. The initial volume of the bubble can be assumed to be zero. Find the rate, in cm s-1, at which the radius","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"6","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 6]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.6—Differentiating polynomials n E Q. Chain, product and quotient rules","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.14—Implicit functions, related rates, optimisation","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.1—3d space, volume, angles, distance, midpoints"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}